<author><name><![CDATA[goto80]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-08-24T07:58:26-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-08-24T07:58:26-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5397&amp;p=50186#p50186</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5397&amp;p=50186#p50186"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[History of The Single Voice Echo?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5397&amp;p=50186#p50186"><![CDATA[
For the C64 there's Hysteria, subsong 3 (Fred Gray 1987) which has a delay of sorts, using PWM. Supercan (Lars Hård 1986) uses delay around 02.20, but it's only one step so it's not that obvious. <br /><br />I'm actually surprised I didn't find more (even with the help of those CSDb-forums), but it's a tricky thing to look for. And yeah, neither of these are very extensive use of delay anyway.<br /><br />But it sure seems like C64 was first. <img src="http://forums.nesdev.com/images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4027">goto80</a> — Mon Aug 24, 2009 7:58 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
