<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[mic_]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-07-15T02:25:32-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-07-15T02:25:32-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5397&amp;p=48884#p48884</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5397&amp;p=48884#p48884"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[History of The Single Voice Echo?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5397&amp;p=48884#p48884"><![CDATA[
The game itself is actually quite bad. The music is decent, but nothing memorable. What I remember mostly about Rockin' Kats is the <a href="http://www.akterhall.com/Nintendo%20SM%201992.htm" class="postlink">bus that Nintendo's Swedish publisher drove around with in 1992</a>. It had a bunch of NESs and TVs lined up on both sides of the aisle where you could play upcoming games for a while (then you had to get out and stand in line again). Among the games you could play (that I can remember) were Rockin' Kats, Batman : Return of the Joker and Darkman.<br /><br />Shadowgate and Deja Vu do indeed use a lot of echoes. Both are pretty good too, though I might be biased because I played them so much at the time (to the point where one of my friends got banned from playing video games on school nights by his parents).<br /><br />As far as echoes goes, I don't know if anyone has mentioned Robo Warrior, but it uses them a bit. Real good game too, and a good soundtrack.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1181">mic_</a> — Wed Jul 15, 2009 2:25 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
